snippet.textDisplay: I used espresso powder and super fine sugar (equal parts initially led to a too bitter foam, had to adjust the ratios) and then used it to make a variant of a Churchill’s Breakfast cocktail (traditionally rye-cold brew coffee-maple syrup-angostura bitters-cinnamon). I replaced the cold brew with this foam. Tried shaking everything except the Dalgona and then floated it on top. This was OK, but not quite there. I then did a shake with everything including some Dalgona and then strained into a coupe and topped with a bit of the Dalgona... this was exactly what I was shooting for. Cheers! 🥃

snippet.textDisplay: The secret of making this foamy coffee easier is adding VERY LITTLE amount of water! In my case, I add 2 tsp of instant coffee, 2 tsp of sugar and 1 tsp of water (or LESS) in a NARROW CUP; then whisk with WOODEN SPOON. It takes less than 1 minute to form a light beige colored, creamy consistency. I use this method to make iced coffee: add cold water and mix well so the foamy coffee dissolves in water; then add ice. I don't usually add milk because the foamy coffee already gives this soft creamy taste. It is not exactly Dalgona coffee recipe... just the way I drink my iced coffee...

snippet.textDisplay: You could probably use the freeze concentration method on your espresso. Freeze it solid, take it out of the freezer and put it onto a siv placed over a cup. The coffee will melt first and drip down into the cup. Don't wait for too long as the water will start melting as well and slowly drip back into your espresso concentrate. I've used this technique before on apple juice and you can easily remove 50% of the water this way. Some of the flavours will stay in the water but you could just stick the lump of ice back into the freezer and reuse as the ice for your Dalgona.

Would be interesting to hear your thoughts on the canarian coffee drink "Leche Leche" (also called Café con leche y leche condensada). I usually make it like this:

1. 50-60ml (I usually go with 50ml) Condensed sweetened milk
2. A shot of double espresso 60ml
3. 130-140ml frothed milk

The traditional method is a 1/3 ratio for each ingredient but I think it's a bit to sweet at least with the water and coffee we have here.
